  • Full pooling
  • No pooling
  • Partial pooling

Lets collapse the time dimension for now and focus on estimating the death rate in the final year and the 9th month.

data <- data |>
  mutate(provincia_id = data |> group_by(SIGLA) |> group_indices()) |>
  filter(year == 2018) |>
  filter(month == 9)
data |>
  ggplot(aes(x = SIGLA, y = deaths)) +
  geom_jitter()

Estimate the region-specific death rate/relative risk/excess?

Full pooling model

Treat all regions the same and estimate a single national prevalence.

Priors \[ \alpha \sim N(0,5), \\ \sigma_p \sim N^+(1),\\ \theta_j \sim N(0, \sigma^2_p), \quad j=1,..., N_p \] Likelihood: \[ y_i \sim \text{Pois}(\mu_i),\\ \text{log}(\mu_i) = \text{log}(E_i) + \alpha + \theta\\ i=1,..., N \quad (observation) \] Parameter \(\theta\) here is common for all observations \(y_i\), regardless of what province the observation belongs to.

No pooling model

Treat all regions separately and estimate each region separately with fixed effects.

Partial pooling model

Varying intercepts model. Random effect grouping all regions. Estimate hyperparamter sigma (explain how this is hierarchical)

Priors: \[ \alpha \sim N(0,5), \\ \sigma_p \sim N^+(1),\\ \theta_j \sim N(0, \sigma^2_p), \quad j=1,..., N_p \]

Likelihood: \[ y_i \sim \text{Pois}(\mu_i),\\ \text{log}(\mu_i) = \text{log}(E_i) + \alpha + \theta_j\\ i=1,..., N \quad (observation) \\ j=1,..., N_p \quad (province) \\ \]

constants <- list(
  N = nrow(data),
  Np = max(data$provincia_id),
  province = data$provincia_id
)

inits <- list(
  alpha = 0,
  theta = rep(0, constants$Np),
  sigma_p = 1
)

nimble_data <- list(
  y = as.integer(data$deaths),
  E = data$expected
)
partial_pooling_model <- nimbleCode({
  # priors
  alpha ~ dnorm(0, 5)
  sigma_p ~ T(dnorm(0, 1), 0, Inf) # half-normal

  for (j in 1:Np) {
    theta[j] ~ dnorm(0, sd = sigma_p)
  }

  # likelihood
  for (i in 1:N) {
    y[i] ~ dpois(mu[i])
    log(mu[i]) <- log(E[i]) + alpha + theta[province[i]]
  }
})
